Refresh spi driver at V27.

This needs to add `ARM64`, so that if we remove `COMPILE_TEST`, it still could be enabled.

```
depends on ARM || ARM64 || COMPILE_TEST
```
I have updated this patch. Thanks.
From my testing on aspeed-sdk, this defconfig will produce a kernel image that is big enough that will reach the kernel region size if some extra config is enabled.

We will use lzma compressed algorithm instead of gzip to save the code size.
```
FIT_KERNEL_COMP_ALG ?= "lzma"
FIT_KERNEL_COMP_ALG_EXTENSION ?= ".lzma"
```

It also require this commit into OpenBMC.
https://patchwork.yoctoproject.org/project/oe-core/patch/20241120061724.851003-1-jamin_lin@aspeedtech.com/
In aspeed sdk,`UBOOT_SIGN_ENABLE` is enabled by default, is it necessary?

The reason why I ask is because the built u-boot only contains the u-boot and dtb, and it does not contain the atf and optee. The built u-boot image fails to boot on the real board.

Could you check and possible make sure the atf and optee are built by default?

The UBOOT_SIGN_ENABLE is not necessary

In the Aspeed SDK, UBOOT_SIGN_ENABLE also requires enabling aspeed-secure-cot.inc. Refer to https://github.com/AspeedTech-BMC/openbmc/blob/aspeed-master/meta-aspeed-sdk/meta-ast2600-sdk/conf/machine/include/ast2600-secure-mode.inc#L1. Currently, it only supports AST2600.

The meta-aspeed doesn't enable UBOOT_SIGN_ENABLE for AST2600, so I haven't enabled it for AST2700.

Regarding atf and optee, you can see my commit log. It depends on commit:
https://patchwork.yoctoproject.org/project/oe-core/patch/20240119061937.1368163-4-jamin_lin@aspeedtech.com/

V20~V22: update for new yocto.
V23: update SPI dirver to fix build fail.
V24: update ethernet and mdio dirver.
V25: update for uboot-sign v5 version.
     update dts for new mdio driver.
Done
Is `UBOOT_FIT_TEE` necessary? It's missing and without this, the u-boot will not include the optee image.
It include in meta-aspeed/conf/machine/include/ast-optee-os.inc.
The kernel size of 9MiB is too limited for ast27x0, possibly we could adjust openbmc-flash-layout-128.dtsi to update both u-boot and kernel partitions.

I added aspeed-flash-layout-128.dtsi for the AST2700 flash layout in this patch file.

V25: Use lzma compressed algorithm to reduce the kernel size. (kernel size becomes 6.4KB) 
FIT_KERNEL_COMP_ALG ?= "lzma"
FIT_KERNEL_COMP_ALG_EXTENSION ?= ".lzma"

I think 9MiB for ast27x0's kernel is too limited, why not increase this partition and reduce the rofs size?

In openbmc tree, we could define a new layout to make it work with this dts as well.

If using the AST2600/AST2700 DCSCM board, the SPI size is 256MB, but the BMC partition size is only 64MB. I am trying to use the same U-Boot and Kernel partition sizes on both the DCSCM board and the EVB board.

It's OK to keep the u-boot/u-boot-env partitioins the same for 128 and 256 MiB flash, but kernel partition could be adjusted to fit the need.
We will use the different flash layout dts for 128/256 MiB anyway, so we could specify the kernel partition size in each dts.
